    <h2>Understanding Spousal Support in Maryland</h2>
    <p>
      Spousal support — commonly referred to as alimony — is financial support paid by one spouse to the other during or after a Maryland divorce proceeding. Maryland law recognizes several types of spousal support, each serving a different purpose and governed by different legal standards.
    </p>
    <p>
      At Child Custody with a Plan, our attorneys have extensive experience representing both support-seeking and support-paying spouses in Maryland alimony proceedings. We serve clients from our offices in <strong>Rockville</strong> and <strong>Baltimore</strong>, across all Maryland counties.
    </p>

    <h2>Types of Spousal Support in Maryland</h2>

    <h3>Pendente Lite Support (Temporary Alimony)</h3>
    <p>
      <em>Pendente lite</em> is Latin for "pending litigation." This type of support is ordered by a Maryland court to maintain the financial status quo during the divorce proceedings — before the final divorce decree is entered. Its purpose is to ensure that neither spouse is financially devastated while the divorce is pending.
    </p>
    <p>
      Pendente lite support is typically calculated based on the parties' actual financial circumstances at the time of the hearing. Our attorneys act quickly to secure or defend against pendente lite orders, understanding that temporary support decisions can set important precedents.
    </p>

    <h3>Rehabilitative Alimony</h3>
    <p>
      Rehabilitative alimony is the most common type of long-term spousal support in Maryland. It is designed to support a dependent spouse while they take steps to become self-supporting — through education, job training, re-entering the workforce, or developing earning capacity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Rehabilitative alimony is awarded for a specific period of time, determined by how long it will reasonably take the receiving spouse to achieve financial independence. Our attorneys work to establish — or challenge — the length and amount of rehabilitative alimony based on a thorough analysis of the relevant factors.
    </p>

    <h3>Indefinite (Permanent) Alimony</h3>
    <p>
      Indefinite alimony is awarded only in limited circumstances under Maryland law — typically when the receiving spouse is unable to become self-supporting due to age, illness, or disability, OR when the disparity in the parties' standards of living would be unconscionable even after a spouse becomes self-supporting.
    </p>
    <p>
      Indefinite alimony cases require compelling evidence. Our attorneys are experienced in both pursuing and defending against indefinite alimony claims in Maryland Circuit Court.
    </p>

    <h2>Factors Maryland Courts Consider for Spousal Support</h2>
    <p>
      Under Maryland Code, Family Law § 11-106, courts consider the following factors in awarding alimony:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The ability of the party seeking alimony to be wholly or partly self-supporting</li>
      <li>The time necessary to gain sufficient education or training to enable the party seeking alimony to find suitable employment</li>
      <li>The standard of living that the parties established during their marriage</li>
      <li>The duration of the marriage</li>
      <li>The contributions, monetary and nonmonetary, of each party to the wellbeing of the family</li>
      <li>The circumstances that contributed to the estrangement of the parties</li>
      <li>The age of each party</li>
      <li>The physical and mental condition of each party</li>
      <li>The ability of the party from whom alimony is sought to meet their own needs while meeting the needs of the party seeking alimony</li>
      <li>Any agreement between the parties</li>
      <li>The financial needs and financial resources of each party</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Spousal Support Modification in Maryland</h2>
    <p>
      Alimony orders are not always permanent. Maryland law allows for modification of rehabilitative alimony when there has been a <strong>material change in circumstances</strong> — such as a significant change in either party's income, the receiving spouse's remarriage, or cohabitation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whether you need to seek a modification or defend against one, our attorneys develop a strategic approach supported by solid financial evidence and legal argument.
    </p>

    <h2>Spousal Support Enforcement</h2>
    <p>
      If your former spouse is failing to comply with a court-ordered spousal support obligation, Maryland courts have enforcement mechanisms available, including wage garnishment and contempt proceedings. Our attorneys act swiftly to enforce support orders and protect your financial rights.
    </p>

    <h2>Tax Considerations in Maryland Spousal Support</h2>
    <p>
      Under current federal tax law (post-Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017), alimony paid pursuant to divorce agreements executed after December 31, 2018 is neither deductible by the payor nor includable in the income of the recipient. This change has significant financial implications for how support agreements should be structured. Our attorneys help clients understand and navigate these tax consequences.
    </p>

